> ### Golang/Gin codebase containing real world examples (CRUD, auth, advanced patterns, etc) that adheres to the [RealWorld](https://github.com/gothinkster/realworld) spec and API.


This codebase was created to demonstrate a fully fledged fullstack application built with **Golang/Gin** including CRUD operations, authentication, routing, pagination, and more.


# Directory structure
```
.
├── gorm.db
├── hello.go
├── common
│   ├── utils.go        //small tools function
│   └── database.go     //DB connect manager
├── users
|   ├── models.go       //data models define & DB operation
|   ├── serializers.go  //response computing & format
|   ├── routers.go      //business logic & router binding
|   ├── middlewares.go  //put the before & after logic of handle request
|   └── validators.go   //form/json checker
├── ...
...
```

# Getting started

## Install Golang

Make sure you have Go 1.13 or higher installed.

https://golang.org/doc/install

## Environment Config

Set-up the standard Go environment variables according to latest guidance (see https://golang.org/doc/install#install).


## Install Dependencies
From the project root, run:
```
go build ./...
go test ./...
go mod tidy
```

## Testing
From the project root, run:
```
go test ./...
```
or
```
go test ./... -cover
```
or
```
go test -v ./... -cover
```
depending on whether you want to see test coverage and how verbose the output you want.

message.content:
Primary language: Go (Golang)

Primary development framework: Gin (github.com/gin-gonic/gin)

Evidence and explanation:
- The repository contains go.mod, go.sum and .go source files (hello.go, doc.go, etc.), confirming this is a Go project.
- go.mod lists dependencies including github.com/gin-gonic/gin v1.8.1 and github.com/jinzhu/gorm, showing the use of Gin as the HTTP framework and GORM as the ORM.
- hello.go imports "github.com/gin-gonic/gin" and its main() calls gin.Default(), defines route groups (r.Group("/api")), uses middleware (v1.Use(users.AuthMiddleware(...))) and r.Run(), which are canonical Gin usage patterns.

Additional context: this is the Golang/Gin RealWorld example app (implements REST routes, auth, and CRUD), so Gin is the primary web framework while GORM is used for database/model work.
